":"1488","1452":"1452","1540":"1540","1485":"1485","about 1440":"about 1440","1549":"1549","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Howley, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mirfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Mirfield (WR Yorks)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Oliver","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a French name, <i>Olivier</i>, recorded as the name of one of Charlemagne's paladins (retainers), the close companion in arms of Roland in the Chanson de Roland. Whereas Roland is headstrong and rash, Oliver is thoughtful and cautious. Ostensibly this name derives from Late Latin <i>olivarius</i> ‘olive tree’ (  compare  Olive  ), but Charlemagne's other paladins all bear solidly Germanic names, so it is more probably an altered form of a Germanic name, perhaps distantly connected with Old Norse <i>Óleifr</i> ‘ancestral relic’. It has remained in more or less continuous use since the medieval period, becoming ever more popular since the 1980s."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":15,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705201,"age":109,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":118,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Oliver Mirfield was born about 1440, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Oliver Merfield, was 71 and his mother, Isabel Eland, was 61. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Isabel Savile. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1440–":"umbes 1440–Surnud","1390–1485":"1390–1485","1391–Female":"1391–Surnud","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1440–1488":"1440–1488","1452–Male":"1452–Surnud","1460–1522":"1460–1522","–1540":"–1540","1370–1448":"1370–1448","1380–1448":"1380–1448","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1558":"1558","1448":"1448","Abt 1460":"umbes 1460","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1452":"1452","1540":"1540","1485":"1485","about 1440":"umbes 1440","1549":"1549","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Howley, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1440–":"noin 1440–Kuollut","1390–1485":"1390–1485","1391–Female":"1391–Kuollut","1440–Male":"1440–Kuollut","1440–1488":"1440–1488","1452–Male":"1452–Kuollut","1460–1522":"1460–1522","–1540":"–1540","1370–1448":"1370–1448","1380–1448":"1380–1448","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1558":"1558","1448":"1448",